{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}} {{Infobox officeholder | honorific-prefix = | name = James Clark | image = James McCosh Clark, ca 1885-1889.jpg | caption = James Clark in the 1880s | order = 8th | office = Mayor of Auckland City | term_start = 1880 | term_end = 1883 | predecessor = [[Thomas Peacock (politician)|Thomas Peacock]] | successor = [[William Waddel]] | birth_date = {{birth date|1833|08|12|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Beith]], Scotland | death_date = {{death date and age|1898|01|26|1833|08|12|df=y}} | death_place = England | spouse = Kate Emma Clark | relations = [[Archibald Clark (politician)|Archibald Clark]] (father) | party = [[Independent politician|Independent]]}}
'''James McCosh Clark''' (12 August 1833 – 26 January 1898) was mayor of Auckland, New Zealand, in the 1880s. He was a successful businessman until many of his ventures failed during the depression of the 1880s, causing him to return to England for the last decade of his life. He was the son of [[Archibald Clark (politician)|Archibald Clark]].
==Early life== Clark was born in [[Beith]], Scotland, in 1833, the eldest son of the merchant [[Archibald Clark (politician)|Archibald Clark]] and his first wife, Margaret McCosh.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark">{{DNZB|McCallum|Janet |2c18|Clark, Kate Emma – Biography|18 September 2011}}</ref> He was educated at [[Largs]].<ref name="Ardrossan and Saltcoats Herald obit">{{cite news|title=Mr. James McCosh Clark|url=http://gilliandr.wordpress.com/2009/07/01/death-of-a-native-of-beith-1898/|accessdate=19 September 2011|newspaper=Ardrossan and Saltcoats Herald|date=4 February 1898|page=5}}</ref> Archibald Clark decided to emigrate to New Zealand with his third wife and four children; the family left London on the barque ''Thames'' on 18 July 1849 and arrived in [[Auckland]] on 25 November.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Shipping Lists|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=DSC18491127.2.3|accessdate=26 September 2011|newspaper=Daily Southern Cross|volume=V |issue=252 |date=27 November 1849|page=2}}</ref><ref name="Archibald Clark & Sons">{{cite news|title=Archibald Clark & Sons, Limited.|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=TO19080815.2.70|accessdate=17 September 2011|newspaper=Observer|volume=XXVIII |issue=48 |date=15 August 1908|page=38}}</ref> He joined the Volunteer Forces and was a captain in the [[Invasion of Waikato]] in 1863.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" />
==Professional life== Clark joined his father's company as a partner in 1856 or 1857, and the company was renamed Archibald Clark and Sons.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" /> They manufactured clothing and were a wholesaler, at one time employing some 500 staff.{{sfn|Cyclopedia Company Limited|1902|p=103}} Clark became the senior partner following his father's death in October 1875. He was involved in numerous other companies. His investment in the Moanataiari gold mining company made him a rich man.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" /> Moanataiari is now a suburb of [[Thames, New Zealand|Thames]] in the [[Coromandel Peninsula|Coromandel]].
Together with [[John Logan Campbell (politician)|John Logan Campbell]], [[Gustav von der Heyde]], [[John Shera]] and others, Clark set up the New Zealand Freight Company in 1872, which amalgamated with the New Zealand Shipping Company the following year.{{sfn|Brett |1924 |p=359}} All the Auckland shipping owners combined into one company in 1881, the [[Northern Steamship Company|Northern Steam Ship Company]], of which Clark was appointed one of the directors.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Birth of the Northern Steam Ship Company |url= http://www.nzmaritimeindex.org.nz/nssco/birth.htm |publisher=Voyager New Zealand Maritime Museum|accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref> The depression in the second half of the 1880s affected this company,<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaky Beginnings 1881–1887 |url= http://www.nzmaritimeindex.org.nz/nssco/shaky_beginnings.htm |publisher=Voyager New Zealand Maritime Museum| accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref> but Clark managed to the secure the services of a new managing director in 1888 who could turn the situation around.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Ranson Period 1887–1921 |url= http://www.nzmaritimeindex.org.nz/nssco/ranson.htm |publisher=Voyager New Zealand Maritime Museum| accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref>
Clark was one of the financial backers of business entrepreneur [[Thomas Russell (New Zealand politician)|Thomas Russell]], who in 1859 had founded the [[NZI|New Zealand Insurance]] (NZI). The group of businessmen and companies behind Russell became known as the Limited Circle, and they were financing much of the development of Auckland. The funds came from the proceeds of the Thames gold rush.<ref name="crony capitalists">{{cite news|last=Hunt|first=Graeme|title=Auckland: Rise of the crony capitalists|url=http://mobile.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.php?c_id=1&objectid=10666749|accessdate=25 September 2011|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|date=25 August 2010}}</ref> Members of the Limited Circle founded the [[Bank of New Zealand]] in 1861 and Clark was on the board of directors.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" /><ref name="crony capitalists" /> He was president of the [[Auckland Chamber of Commerce]] in 1879–1881.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" />
With [[Josiah Firth]], Clark established the Te Aroha Battery Company, a gold mining company. It was one of the many speculative deals which did not go well, and the depression in the second half of the 1880s necessitated a sale, which was done in 1887 incurring a great loss. The [[Thames Valley and Rotorua Railway Company]] was another such venture; it built parts of the [[Rotorua Branch|Rotorua]] and [[Kinleith Branch|Kinleith]] branches before its collapse. While Archibald Clark and Sons prospered, several other of Clark's businesses failed, and having lost his high standing in society, he took his family back to England in 1889.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" />
==Political career== [[File:James McCosh Clark, 1882.jpg|thumb|left|upright|James McCosh Clark in 1882 during his time as [[Mayor of Auckland City|Mayor of Auckland]]]] Clark was a member of the [[Auckland Province|Auckland Provincial Council]], representing the Newton electorate on the 6th Council from December 1869 to September 1870.{{sfn|Scholefield |1950|p=182}}
He was [[Mayor of Auckland City|Mayor of Auckland]] from 1880 to 1883.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" /> In November 1880, 1881 and 1882, respectively, he was elected unopposed on all occasions.<ref>{{cite news|title=The New Mayor|url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=AS18801116.2.36 |accessdate=20 September 2011|newspaper=Auckland Star|volume=XI |issue=3221 |date=16 November 1880|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Auckland|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=DTN18811123.2.22.4|accessdate=20 September 2011|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|date=23 November 1881|issue=3244|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Auckland|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=THS18821117.2.8.2|accessdate=26 September 2011|newspaper=Thames Star|volume=XIII |issue=4331 |date=17 November 1882|page=2}}</ref> During his term in Office, the first [[Trams in New Zealand#Auckland|tramway]] (Horse drawn) was constructed and the site for the [[Auckland Town Hall]] was purchased. Clark's council also decided on the site of the library and art gallery, still occupied today by the [[Auckland Art Gallery]].<ref name="Thames Star obit">{{cite news|title=Death of James McCosh Clark|url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=THS18980128.2.26 |accessdate=19 September 2011|newspaper=Thames Star|volume=XXX |issue=8978 |date=28 January 1898|page=2}}</ref><ref name=register>{{NZHPT|92|Auckland City Art Gallery|20 September 2011}}</ref> On retiring from the mayoralty, he was given a [[telescope]] in appreciation of his services.{{sfn|Cyclopedia Company Limited|1902|p=125}} In 1886–1887, Clark represented the Grafton ward as a Councillor.{{sfn|Cyclopedia Company Limited|1902|p=130}} Other local body roles included the chairmanship of the Auckland Harbour Board and of the Education Board.{{sfn|Cyclopedia Company Limited |1902 |p=126}}
Clark stood for [[New Zealand Parliament|Parliament]] on three occasions.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" /> In the [[New Zealand general election, 1875–76|1875–76 general election]], he was nominated by [[Thomas Peacock (politician)|Thomas Peacock]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Nominations at City East|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=AS18751223.2.26|accessdate=20 September 2011|newspaper=Auckland Star|volume=VI |issue=1827 |date=23 December 1875|page=3}}</ref> but unsuccessfully contested the [[Auckland East]] electorate against [[William Lee Rees]], polling 266 votes against 300.{{sfn|Scholefield |1950|p=134}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Auckland|url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=TH18760101.2.16.1 |accessdate=20 September 2011|newspaper=Taranaki Herald|volume=XXIV |issue=2373 |date=1 January 1876|page=2}}</ref> Clark then contested the Auckland East electorate in the [[New Zealand general election, 1879|1879 general election]] against [[William Speight]] and was narrowly defeated with 363 to 371 votes.<ref>{{cite news|title=The City East Election|url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=AS18790915.2.43 |accessdate=20 September 2011|newspaper=Auckland Star|volume=X |issue=2939 |date=15 September 1879|page=3}}</ref>
Clark was re-elected mayor in 1881 and declared that he would not stand in the [[New Zealand general election, 1881|1881 general election]], as he could not do justice to both commitments, but he changed his mind when it was announced that Sir [[George Grey]] would stand in Auckland East. It is said that Clark did not intend to be elected, he merely stood to oppose and defeat Grey.<ref>{{cite news|title=The True Story of City East Election|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=TO18811217.2.20|accessdate=20 September 2011|newspaper=Observer|volume=3 |issue=66 |date=17 December 1881|page=216}}</ref> The results were 349 and 315 votes for Grey and Clark, respectively, and Grey was declared elected with a majority of 34 votes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Poll Declarations|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=AS18811210.2.19.1|accessdate=20 September 2011|newspaper=Auckland Star|volume=XII |issue=3540 |date=10 December 1881|page=2}}</ref>
==Private life== Clark was active in the [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian Church]] and was the national treasurer for ten years from 1862. In 1865, he purchased The Tower, a large house in Remuera, as his residence. The building is these days part of [[King's School (Auckland)|King's School]].<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" />
He married Kate Emma McCosh Clark (née Woolnough) on 8 April 1875 in Melbourne. Two days later, on a Saturday, the Auckland premises of Archibald Clark and Sons were closed to give staff the opportunity to celebrate the wedding at.<ref>{{cite news|title= Untitled|url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=AS18750410.2.8 |accessdate=26 September 2011|newspaper=Auckland Star|volume=VI |issue=1609 |date=10 April 1875|page=2}}</ref> His wife was born at [[Ipswich]], Suffolk, England in 1847. She studied art and lived in London, earning a living by undertaking research for writers. They had five children while they lived in Auckland, and their first son was born on 28 December 1875.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Birth|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=AS18751229.2.7|accessdate=26 September 2011|newspaper=Auckland Star|volume=VI |issue=1830 |date=29 December 1875|page=2}}</ref>
After many of Clark's businesses had failed, the family migrated to London.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" />{{sfn|Platts|1980 |p=158}} While there Kate Emma McCosh Clark wrote the first New Zealand children's story ''A southern cross fairy tale'', which she partly illustrated, published in London in 1891. Her last work ''Maori tales and legends'' (1896), was intended to interest and instruct young people about New Zealand and the Maori. In early 1898, they were making plans to return to New Zealand.<ref name="Ardrossan and Saltcoats Herald obit" />
==Death== Clark died on 26 January 1898 at [[St Leonards-on-Sea]]. He was survived by his wife and his five children.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" /><ref name="Ardrossan and Saltcoats Herald obit" /> His wife returned to New Zealand in 1900 and died at Auckland on 3 November 1926.<ref name="DNZB McCosh Clark" />
